    {"question": "What is a dividend yield?", "options": ["The total dividends ever paid", "The annual dividend payment divided by the stock price", "A yield sign on Wall Street", "The maximum dividend possible"], "correct": 1, "explanation": "A 4% dividend yield on a CHF 100 stock means CHF 4 in annual dividends."},
    {"question": "What is hyperinflation?", "options": ["Very fast inflation, exceeding 50% per month", "Normal inflation", "Deflation", "Slow economic growth"], "correct": 0, "explanation": "Hyperinflation destroys currency value rapidly, as seen in Zimbabwe and Venezuela."},
    {"question": "What is stagflation?", "options": ["A stag party on Wall Street", "High inflation combined with high unemployment and stagnant growth", "Fast economic growth", "Low inflation with low unemployment"], "correct": 1, "explanation": "Stagflation is particularly challenging because traditional economic tools work against each other."},
    {"question": "What is a 'golden cross'?", "options": ["A golden-colored necklace", "When a short-term moving average crosses above a long-term one", "A type of gold investment", "An award for best investor"], "correct": 1, "explanation": "A golden cross is seen as a bullish signal by technical analysts."},
    {"question": "What is a 'death cross'?", "options": ["A dangerous intersection", "When a short-term moving average crosses below a long-term one", "A bankruptcy filing", "A type of insurance product"], "correct": 1, "explanation": "A death cross is seen as a bearish signal by technical analysts."},
    {"question": "What is a sovereign wealth fund?", "options": ["A king's personal savings", "A state-owned investment fund", "A type of government bond", "A charity fund"], "correct": 1, "explanation": "Countries like Norway and Singapore manage massive sovereign wealth funds from surplus revenues."},
    {"question": "What is a conglomerate?", "options": ["A type of rock", "A corporation made up of several different businesses", "A gathering of investors", "A type of bond"], "correct": 1, "explanation": "Conglomerates like Berkshire Hathaway operate across many different industries."},
    {"question": "What is a stock buyback?", "options": ["Returning a stock to the store", "When a company purchases its own shares from the market", "Buying back a sold stock at a loss", "A government program"], "correct": 1, "explanation": "Buybacks reduce shares outstanding, potentially increasing earnings per share and stock price."},
    {"question": "What is a fiduciary duty?", "options": ["A tax obligation", "A legal obligation to act in someone else's best interest", "A duty to file reports", "A trading requirement"], "correct": 1, "explanation": "Financial advisors with fiduciary duty must prioritize your interests over their own."},
    {"question": "What is a circuit breaker in stock markets?", "options": ["An electrical safety device", "A mechanism that temporarily halts trading during extreme price moves", "A type of power outage", "A trading strategy"], "correct": 1, "explanation": "Circuit breakers prevent panic selling by pausing trading when markets drop too fast."},
    {"question": "What is a secondary market?", "options": ["A market that opens second", "Where previously issued securities are bought and sold between investors", "A less important market", "A market for second-hand goods"], "correct": 1, "explanation": "Stock exchanges are secondary markets where investors trade existing securities."},
    {"question": "What is a primary market?", "options": ["The most important market", "Where new securities are issued and sold for the first time", "A farmer's market", "The largest market by volume"], "correct": 1, "explanation": "IPOs and new bond issuances happen in the primary market."},
    {"question": "What is a yield curve?", "options": ["A curvy road on Wall Street", "A graph showing interest rates across different bond maturities", "A type of stock chart", "A measure of stock performance"], "correct": 1, "explanation": "An inverted yield curve often predicts recessions."},
    {"question": "What is quantitative tightening?", "options": ["A weight-loss program", "When central banks reduce their balance sheet by selling bonds", "A strict budgeting plan", "A type of stock split"], "correct": 1, "explanation": "QT is the opposite of QE and can lead to higher interest rates and reduced liquidity."},
    {"question": "What is a custodian in finance?", "options": ["A janitor at a bank", "A financial institution that holds and safeguards securities", "A type of investment advisor", "A government regulator"], "correct": 1, "explanation": "Custodians hold your assets securely and handle settlements and record-keeping."},
    {"question": "What is a 'moat' in investing?", "options": ["A ditch around a castle", "A company's sustainable competitive advantage", "A type of barrier to investing", "A trading floor feature"], "correct": 1, "explanation": "Companies with wide moats can maintain profits and market dominance over time."},
    {"question": "What is a junk bond?", "options": ["A worthless bond", "A high-yield bond with a credit rating below investment grade", "A bond from a junkyard company", "A recycled bond"], "correct": 1, "explanation": "Junk bonds offer higher yields to compensate for their higher default risk."},
    {"question": "What is a basis point?", "options": ["A point on a base", "One hundredth of a percentage point (0.01%)", "The starting point of a stock", "A score in a trading game"], "correct": 1, "explanation": "If interest rates move from 2.00% to 2.25%, that's a 25 basis point increase."},
    {"question": "What is de-dollarization?", "options": ["Converting dollars to another currency", "A global trend of reducing the US dollar's role in international trade", "Destroying dollar bills", "A type of currency exchange"], "correct": 1, "explanation": "Some countries are diversifying away from the dollar in trade and reserves."},
    {"question": "What is a flash crash?", "options": ["A camera malfunction", "An extremely rapid and deep market drop followed by quick recovery", "A type of lightning", "A computer error trading pattern"], "correct": 1, "explanation": "Flash crashes are usually caused by algorithmic trading and panic-driven liquidity withdrawal."},
    {"question": "What is DeFi?", "options": ["A type of defibrillator", "Decentralized Finance — financial services on blockchain without intermediaries", "A coding language", "The definition of finance"], "correct": 1, "explanation": "DeFi provides banking services like lending and trading through smart contracts."},
    {"question": "What is an NFT?", "options": ["Not For Trading", "A Non-Fungible Token — a unique digital asset on a blockchain", "A type of ETF", "A new financial tool"], "correct": 1, "explanation": "NFTs are unique digital certificates of ownership, though their value is highly speculative."},
    {"question": "What is a stablecoin?", "options": ["A very stable investment", "A cryptocurrency pegged to a stable asset like the US dollar", "A coin that doesn't move", "A type of gold coin"], "correct": 1, "explanation": "Stablecoins aim to maintain a 1:1 peg with traditional currencies like the USD."},
    {"question": "What is tax-loss harvesting?", "options": ["Harvesting tax documents", "Selling losing investments to offset capital gains taxes", "A farming tax benefit", "Collecting tax refunds"], "correct": 1, "explanation": "Tax-loss harvesting can reduce your tax bill while maintaining portfolio exposure."},
    {"question": "What is a total return?", "options": ["Your total investment amount", "Capital gains plus dividends and interest combined", "The fee your broker charges", "The maximum possible return"], "correct": 1, "explanation": "Total return captures all sources of investment return, not just price appreciation."},
    {"question": "What is a drawdown?", "options": ["A sketch drawn in a meeting", "The peak-to-trough decline in portfolio value", "A type of dividend", "When a stock is delisted"], "correct": 1, "explanation": "Maximum drawdown measures the worst loss from peak to trough in a given period."},
    {"question": "What is a trailing stop?", "options": ["A hiking trail stop", "A stop-loss order that moves with the stock price", "A delayed trade", "A type of mutual fund"], "correct": 1, "explanation": "Trailing stops automatically adjust to lock in profits as the stock price rises."},
    {"question": "What is a whitepaper in crypto?", "options": ["A blank piece of paper", "A document explaining a cryptocurrency project's technology and purpose", "A government report", "A bank statement"], "correct": 1, "explanation": "Bitcoin's whitepaper by Satoshi Nakamoto started the entire cryptocurrency movement."},
    {"question": "What is a custodial wallet?", "options": ["A wallet held by a janitor", "A crypto wallet where a third party holds and manages your private keys", "A physical leather wallet", "A type of investment account"], "correct": 1, "explanation": "Custodial wallets are convenient but mean you don't fully control your crypto."},
    {"question": "What is tokenization?", "options": ["Creating arcade tokens", "Converting real-world assets into digital tokens on a blockchain", "A type of encryption", "A game mechanic"], "correct": 1, "explanation": "Tokenization could transform real estate, art, and other asset classes by making them more liquid."},
    {"question": "What is the 60/40 portfolio?", "options": ["60 stocks and 40 bonds in total", "A classic allocation of 60% stocks and 40% bonds", "A portfolio with 60% cash", "A retirement age strategy"], "correct": 1, "explanation": "The 60/40 portfolio has been a standard balanced approach for decades."},
    {"question": "What is a covered call strategy?", "options": ["A phone call about coverage", "Selling call options on stocks you already own", "A type of insurance policy", "A defensive driving technique"], "correct": 1, "explanation": "Covered calls generate income from premiums but cap your upside potential."},
    {"question": "What is active vs. passive investing?", "options": ["Active means exercising while investing", "Active involves frequent trading; passive tracks indices", "Active is for professionals only", "There is no difference"], "correct": 1, "explanation": "Passive investing typically outperforms active management over long periods due to lower fees."},
    {"question": "What is a central bank?", "options": ["A bank in the center of town", "An institution that manages a country's money supply and interest rates", "The largest bank by assets", "A bank that only serves governments"], "correct": 1, "explanation": "Central banks like the Fed, ECB, and SNB control monetary policy and financial stability."},
    {"question": "What is monetary policy?", "options": ["A policy about coins", "Central bank actions to control money supply and interest rates", "A government spending plan", "A bank's fee structure"], "correct": 1, "explanation": "Monetary policy uses tools like interest rates and QE to manage economic growth and inflation."},
    {"question": "What is fiscal policy?", "options": ["A policy about fishing", "Government decisions about taxation and spending", "A central bank strategy", "A company's dividend policy"], "correct": 1, "explanation": "Fiscal policy involves government spending and tax decisions to influence the economy."},
    {"question": "What is a current account deficit?", "options": ["Your bank account being overdrawn", "When a country imports more than it exports", "A type of credit card debt", "A banking error"], "correct": 1, "explanation": "Persistent current account deficits can weaken a country's currency."},
    {"question": "What is a trade war?", "options": ["Physical warfare between traders", "When countries impose tariffs and trade barriers against each other", "Competition between brokers", "A stock market game"], "correct": 1, "explanation": "Trade wars can disrupt global supply chains and increase prices for consumers."},
    {"question": "What is a blockchain?", "options": ["A chain of blocks at a construction site", "A distributed digital ledger that records transactions", "A type of encryption key", "A banking network"], "correct": 1, "explanation": "Blockchain technology enables decentralized, transparent, and tamper-resistant record-keeping."},
    {"question": "What is proof of stake?", "options": ["Proving you own a steak", "A consensus mechanism where validators stake crypto to verify transactions", "Showing proof of investment", "A legal document"], "correct": 1, "explanation": "Proof of Stake is more energy-efficient than Proof of Work (used by Bitcoin)."},
    {"question": "What is a halving event in crypto?", "options": ["Cutting a coin in half", "When the reward for mining Bitcoin is cut in half", "A company splitting in two", "A type of stock split"], "correct": 1, "explanation": "Bitcoin halvings occur roughly every 4 years and historically precede price increases."},
    {"question": "What is a private equity fund?", "options": ["A fund run by private individuals", "A fund that invests in private (non-publicly traded) companies", "A secret investment fund", "A type of savings account"], "correct": 1, "explanation": "Private equity funds buy, improve, and sell companies, often requiring large minimum investments."},
    {"question": "What is a venture capital fund?", "options": ["A fund for adventure travel", "A fund that invests in early-stage startups with high growth potential", "A government innovation fund", "A type of pension fund"], "correct": 1, "explanation": "Venture capital funds take high risks for potentially massive returns if startups succeed."},
    {"question": "What is an angel investor?", "options": ["An investor from heaven", "An individual who provides capital to startups in exchange for equity", "A charity donor", "A type of fund manager"], "correct": 1, "explanation": "Angel investors typically invest smaller amounts than venture capital funds an very early stages."},
    {"question": "What is a hostile takeover?", "options": ["A violent event", "When a company acquires another against the target's board wishes", "A friendly business deal", "A type of merger"], "correct": 1, "explanation": "Hostile takeovers often result in premium prices for the target company's shareholders."},
    {"question": "What is a golden parachute?", "options": ["A gold-plated parachute", "A generous severance package for executives during takeovers", "A type of investment guarantee", "An emergency fund"], "correct": 1, "explanation": "Golden parachutes are controversial as they can reward executives even when a company underperforms."},
    {"question": "What is a dead stock?", "options": ["A stock that no longer trades or has very little trading activity", "A stock in a cemetery company", "A profitable stock", "A newly listed stock"], "correct": 0, "explanation": "Dead stocks have minimal trading volume and can be illiquid and hard to sell."},
    {"question": "What is a pre-market trading session?", "options": ["A pre-game warm-up", "Trading that occurs before official market hours", "A type of market research", "A practice trading session"], "correct": 1, "explanation": "Pre-market trading allows investors to react to news before regular hours."},
    {"question": "What is the 'buy and hold' strategy?", "options": ["Buying stocks and physically holding certificates", "Purchasing investments and keeping them for a long period regardless of market fluctuations", "Buying stocks only during holds", "A day trading technique"], "correct": 1, "explanation": "Buy and hold is a proven long-term strategy that avoids the costs of frequent trading."},
    {"question": "What is a warrant?", "options": ["A police document", "A financial instrument giving the right to buy stock at a specific price", "A type of guarantee", "A storage receipt"], "correct": 1, "explanation": "Warrants are similar to options but are issued by the company itself and have longer timeframes."},
    {"question": "What is the efficient market hypothesis?", "options": ["Markets are always right", "The theory that stock prices reflect all available information", "Markets are perfectly efficient", "A theory that markets never crash"], "correct": 1, "explanation": "The EMH suggests it's very difficult to consistently outperform the market through stock picking."},
    {"question": "What is the difference between a broker and an exchange?", "options": ["They are the same thing", "A broker is an intermediary; an exchange is where trades are matched", "Brokers are for stocks; exchanges are for bonds", "An exchange is a type of broker"], "correct": 1, "explanation": "Brokers facilitate your orders; exchanges provide the marketplace where buyers meet sellers."},
    {"question": "What is compound interest?", "options": ["Interest charged by the government on savings", "Interest earned on previously earned interest", "A penalty fee for negative balances", "Interest that only applies in the first year"], "correct": 1, "explanation": "Compound interest means your returns are reinvested and generate their own returns. Over time this creates exponential growth — the most powerful force in long-term investing."},
    {"question": "Which asset class has historically delivered the highest returns over 30 years?", "options": ["Savings account", "Gold", "Stocks (equity market)", "Government bonds"], "correct": 2, "explanation": "Stocks have historically delivered the highest returns over long periods — averaging around 7–10% per year in real terms. This makes them the most important asset class for young long-term investors."},
    {"question": "You are 22 and start investing. What is your biggest advantage over a 50-year-old?", "options": ["You have more money available", "You have a much longer investment horizon", "You pay no taxes", "You know the market better"], "correct": 1, "explanation": "Time is the most valuable factor in investing. With a 40-year horizon, compound interest can reach its full potential. Starting early means you need to invest far less each month than someone who starts late."},
    {"question": "What is an ETF?", "options": ["A government savings product with guaranteed returns", "An exchange-traded fund that tracks an index", "A loan to buy stocks", "An insurance against price losses"], "correct": 1, "explanation": "ETF stands for Exchange Traded Fund. It tracks an index like the S&P 500 and provides broad diversification at very low cost — ideal for beginners."},
    {"question": "What does 'volatility' mean in finance?", "options": ["The annual tax on capital gains", "The degree of price fluctuation of an asset", "The difference between buying and selling price", "The inflation rate of a country"], "correct": 1, "explanation": "Volatility measures how much a price swings up and down. High volatility means large moves in both directions. For long-term investors it is less dangerous because short-term swings even out over time."},
    {"question": "What is the S&P 500?", "options": ["A savings product of the Swiss National Bank", "An index of the 500 largest publicly listed US companies", "A European corporate bond", "A commodity index for oil and gas"], "correct": 1, "explanation": "The S&P 500 contains the 500 largest US companies like Apple, Microsoft and Amazon. It is the most important benchmark for the global stock market and has historically returned around 10% per year."},
    {"question": "Which statement about market timing is correct?", "options": ["Experts can reliably predict the best time to buy", "Catching the perfect moment is nearly impossible long-term", "You should always buy when prices fall", "January is statistically always the best month to buy"], "correct": 1, "explanation": "'Time in the market beats timing the market' — staying invested almost always beats trying to find the perfect moment. Even professional fund managers regularly fail at this."},
    {"question": "What is a dividend?", "options": ["A fee when buying stocks", "A profit distribution from a company to its shareholders", "A repayment amount on bonds", "A tax on capital gains"], "correct": 1, "explanation": "Dividends are portions of a company's profits paid out to shareholders. Reinvesting them gives you a double benefit: price appreciation plus compound interest on the dividends themselves."},
    {"question": "What happens to your purchasing power if you leave money in a savings account with 2% inflation?", "options": ["It stays the same", "It grows because you earn interest", "It decreases if the interest rate is below inflation", "It doubles in 10 years"], "correct": 2, "explanation": "If your savings account pays 0.1% interest but inflation is 2%, you lose 1.9% purchasing power per year in real terms. Long-term investing is one of the few ways to beat inflation."},
    {"question": "What is the difference between a stock and a bond?", "options": ["Stocks are safer than bonds", "A stock makes you a co-owner, a bond means you are lending money", "Bonds are only traded on stock exchanges", "There is no difference"], "correct": 1, "explanation": "A stock makes you a partial owner of a company — you benefit from growth but also bear the risk. A bond is a loan: you lend money and receive interest but have no ownership rights."},
    {"question": "Which strategy do most financial experts recommend for beginners?", "options": ["Buy individual technology stocks", "Regularly invest in broadly diversified ETFs", "Invest only in gold", "Trade derivatives and options"], "correct": 1, "explanation": "Regular investing in low-cost, broadly diversified ETFs is the strategy that delivers the best results for most people. It is simple, inexpensive and proven over decades."},
    {"question": "What is diversification?", "options": ["Investing all savings in the best stock", "Spreading capital across different investments to reduce risk", "Changing your investment strategy every month", "Only investing in domestic companies"], "correct": 1, "explanation": "Diversification means not putting all your eggs in one basket. If one investment loses value, others can compensate. A well-diversified portfolio fluctuates far less than a single stock."},
    {"question": "What is cost averaging?", "options": ["Always buying at the annual low", "Investing the same amount every month regardless of the price", "Averaging the purchase price with the sale price", "Only buying when costs are below the market average"], "correct": 1, "explanation": "With cost averaging you invest a fixed amount regularly. When prices are low you automatically buy more shares, when prices are high you buy fewer. This smooths your average entry price over time."},
    {"question": "What is a market correction?", "options": ["An adjustment of tax laws by the government", "A price decline of at least 10% from the last peak", "An official price setting by the stock exchange", "The alignment of stock prices to their book value"], "correct": 1, "explanation": "A market correction means a drop of at least 10%. It is normal, happens regularly, and is not a disaster. Historically the market has recovered every single time — often stronger than before."},
    {"question": "Which factor has the greatest impact on long-term investment outcomes?", "options": ["Choosing the right broker", "The amount of transaction fees", "How early you start investing", "Monitoring your portfolio daily"], "correct": 2, "explanation": "The earlier you start, the longer compound interest can work. Someone who begins at 20 has an enormous advantage over someone who starts at 35 — even if the latter invests more."},
    {"question": "What is a bear market?", "options": ["A market accessible only to professional traders", "A sustained price decline of more than 20%", "A market with very high trading volume", "A stock exchange phase with particularly low fees"], "correct": 1, "explanation": "A bear market is a sustained decline of 20% or more. For long-term investors it is not a reason to panic — but often a buying opportunity."},
    {"question": "What impact do high fund fees have on long-term returns?", "options": ["None — they are refunded by the government", "A very large one — small differences compound massively over decades", "Fees increase safety so they are worthwhile", "They only matter for short-term investments"], "correct": 1, "explanation": "1% higher fees sounds small — but over 30 years it can cost you 20–30% of your final capital. Low-cost ETFs with 0.1–0.2% fees therefore almost always beat expensive active funds long-term."},
    {"question": "What is an index fund?", "options": ["A fund actively managed by a team of experts", "A fund that automatically tracks a specific market index", "A government fund for retirement savings", "A fund exclusively for institutional investors"], "correct": 1, "explanation": "An index fund tracks an index like the MSCI World automatically and without active management. This makes it inexpensive, transparent and very attractive for long-term investors."},
    {"question": "What is rebalancing?", "options": ["An algorithm that automatically maximises gains", "Regularly adjusting portfolio weights back to the original allocation", "Selling all losing positions", "A fee for transferring stocks"], "correct": 1, "explanation": "Rebalancing means regularly returning your portfolio to its target allocation. If stocks have risen sharply, you sell some and buy bonds — keeping your risk profile stable over time."},
    {"question": "What does it mean when a stock is 'overvalued'?", "options": ["The stock is too expensive for private investors", "The current price is significantly above the fundamental value of the company", "The company is making too much profit", "The government must intervene and lower the price"], "correct": 1, "explanation": "Overvaluation means the market price may be far above what the company is really worth. This increases the risk of a pullback. That is why many long-term investors prefer cheap index funds over individual stocks."},
    {"question": "What is passive investing?", "options": ["You invest money and fall asleep", "You invest in funds that track an index without actively selecting stocks", "You rely on a bank advisor", "You only buy when the market falls"], "correct": 1, "explanation": "Passive investing means simply buying the market — for example via an ETF on the S&P 500. No stock picking, no constant monitoring. Studies show passive strategies beat active fund managers long-term."},
    {"question": "What is an investment savings plan?", "options": ["A government savings programme with guaranteed returns", "An automatic regular purchase of securities with a fixed amount", "A credit plan to finance stock purchases", "An insurance against price losses"], "correct": 1, "explanation": "A savings plan automates investing: a fixed amount is invested in an ETF or fund every month. This eliminates the temptation to wait for the 'right moment'."},
    {"question": "Which statement about cryptocurrencies is most accurate for long-term investors?", "options": ["BTC is risk-free and should dominate the portfolio", "Crypto can be interesting as a small portfolio share but is very volatile", "Cryptocurrencies completely replace stocks", "Crypto is illegal and cannot be purchased"], "correct": 1, "explanation": "Cryptocurrencies can serve as a small part of a portfolio (e.g. 5–10%). However their extreme volatility makes them unsuitable as a core holding — especially for beginners."},
    {"question": "What is the difference between a bull market and a bear market?", "options": ["In a bull market bonds are popular, in a bear market stocks are", "Bull market = rising prices, bear market = falling prices", "Both mean the same thing, just in different countries", "The bull market only applies to commodities"], "correct": 1, "explanation": "In a bull market prices rise steadily — sentiment is optimistic. In a bear market they fall — fear dominates. Both are normal and alternate with each other. Long-term investors benefit from the next bull run."},
    {"question": "How many actively managed equity funds beat their benchmark index over 15 years?", "options": ["More than 80%", "About 50%", "Fewer than 20%", "Exactly 100% — that is what they are paid for"], "correct": 2, "explanation": "Studies consistently show: fewer than 20% of actively managed funds beat their index over 15 years. This is one of the strongest arguments for low-cost index funds."},
    {"question": "What does 'liquidity' mean for an investment?", "options": ["How much water the company consumes", "How quickly and easily an investment can be converted to cash", "Whether the investment is government-insured", "The monthly return of an investment"], "correct": 1, "explanation": "Liquidity describes how quickly you can sell an investment. Stocks and ETFs are highly liquid — you can sell immediately. Real estate or private equity are illiquid — selling can take months."},
    {"question": "Why do experts recommend having an emergency fund before investing?", "options": ["To be able to pay transaction fees", "So that unexpected expenses don't force you to sell investments at the worst moment", "Because banks legally require it", "So you can buy stocks in a bear market"], "correct": 1, "explanation": "Without an emergency fund you risk having to sell investments at a low — exactly when you need the money. Three to six months of living expenses in a savings account is the standard recommendation."},
    {"question": "What is the MSCI World index?", "options": ["An index of the world's poorest countries", "A global equity index with over 1,500 companies from 23 developed countries", "An international currency reserve", "A commodity index of the United Nations"], "correct": 1, "explanation": "The MSCI World covers more than 1,500 companies from 23 developed countries and is the most popular basis for broadly diversified ETFs worldwide."},
    {"question": "What is a drawdown?", "options": ["A withdrawal from a portfolio", "The maximum price decline from peak to trough", "A tax on capital gains", "A special purchase order on the stock exchange"], "correct": 1, "explanation": "The maximum drawdown shows how far a portfolio can fall in a crisis. During the 2008 financial crisis the S&P 500 dropped around 57% — those who stayed invested had fully recovered by 2013."},
    {"question": "What is 'home bias' in investing?", "options": ["The tendency to invest only in real estate", "The tendency to invest too much in your own country", "A preference for online brokers over banks", "A tax deduction for homeowners"], "correct": 1, "explanation": "Many investors put too much in their home country, which increases risk. Holding only domestic stocks means being heavily dependent on that one economy. Global diversification protects against this."},
    {"question": "What happens to a CHF 10,000 investment at 8% return after 30 years?", "options": ["CHF 18,000", "CHF 34,000", "CHF 100,627", "CHF 240,000"], "correct": 2, "explanation": "Thanks to compound interest, CHF 10,000 grows to over CHF 100,000 at 8% over 30 years. That is more than ten times the original — without any additional contributions. This is the power of a long investment horizon."},
    {"question": "What is the difference between nominal and real return?", "options": ["Nominal return is guaranteed, real return is not", "Real return accounts for inflation, nominal return does not", "There is no difference", "Nominal return only applies to bonds"], "correct": 1, "explanation": "If your portfolio earns 7% nominal return and inflation is 2%, your real return is only 5%. That is the amount by which your purchasing power has actually increased."},
    {"question": "Which emotion is most dangerous for investors in a bear market?", "options": ["Curiosity", "Panic", "Patience", "Satisfaction"], "correct": 1, "explanation": "Panic causes investors to sell at the bottom — exactly the wrong time. Studies show that emotional decisions are the single biggest destroyer of returns for private investors."},
    {"question": "What is the risk-return tradeoff?", "options": ["The legal maximum return for private investors", "The principle that higher expected returns come with higher risk", "A government rating for financial products", "The correlation between inflation and interest rates"], "correct": 1, "explanation": "Higher return expectations always come with higher risk. Anyone promising high gains without risk is lying. Understanding this relationship is one of the most important foundations of investing."},
    {"question": "What is a robo-advisor?", "options": ["A robot that physically buys stocks", "An automated digital platform that manages portfolios using algorithms", "An AI system that predicts prices", "A government investment advisor for young people"], "correct": 1, "explanation": "Robo-advisors automatically manage portfolios based on your risk profile. They are cheaper than traditional advisors and ideal for beginners who want a hands-off approach."},
    {"question": "What describes the 'anchoring effect' in investing?", "options": ["Only investing in port cities", "Over-relying on a reference value like the purchase price when making decisions", "Buying stocks of shipbuilding companies", "Always waiting for a specific return before selling"], "correct": 1, "explanation": "The anchoring effect causes investors to hold a stock because they are fixated on the price they paid. Good decisions are based on the current situation — not the past."},
    {"question": "What is sector rotation?", "options": ["Switching from one broker to another", "Shifting capital between different economic sectors", "A legally required change of fund managers", "The annual reweighting of the SMI"], "correct": 1, "explanation": "Different sectors perform better in different economic phases — technology in an upswing, consumer staples in a recession. For beginners, broad diversification across all sectors is the simpler strategy."},
    {"question": "What is the difference between short-term trading and long-term investing?", "options": ["There is no difference", "Trading exploits short-term price movements, investing bets on long-term growth", "Trading is safer, investing is riskier", "Investing is only for the wealthy, trading is for everyone"], "correct": 1, "explanation": "Trading tries to profit from short-term price moves — which leads to losses for most private individuals over time. Long-term investing bets on economic growth over years and decades."},
    {"question": "If you invest CHF 200 per month from age 25, how much do you have at 65 (at 7% p.a.)?", "options": ["CHF 48,000", "CHF 120,000", "CHF 525,000", "CHF 2,400,000"], "correct": 2, "explanation": "CHF 200 per month over 40 years at 7% return yields around CHF 525,000. You only contributed CHF 96,000 — the rest is compound interest. This shows how powerful starting early really is."},
    {"question": "What are emerging markets?", "options": ["New companies that are just going public", "Fast-growing economies like China, India or Brazil", "Markets for sustainable energy", "Regional markets within Switzerland"], "correct": 1, "explanation": "Emerging markets are developing economies with high growth potential. They are riskier than developed markets but offer attractive long-term returns and improve global diversification."},
    {"question": "Which statement about investing psychology is correct?", "options": ["Losses feel about twice as bad as equivalent gains feel good", "Gains always feel more intense than losses", "People react rationally to price fluctuations", "Emotions play no role in investing"], "correct": 0, "explanation": "Behavioural economics shows that losses hurt psychologically about twice as much as equivalent gains bring pleasure. This causes investors to sell too early — to their own detriment."},
    {"question": "What is a value investor like Warren Buffett?", "options": ["Someone who only invests in cheap ETFs", "Someone who seeks undervalued companies and holds them long-term", "Someone who trades daily to capture small gains", "Someone who invests exclusively in gold"], "correct": 1, "explanation": "Value investors seek companies trading below their intrinsic value and hold them for years. Buffett has held some stocks for decades — a prime example of long-term thinking."},
    {"question": "What does TER (Total Expense Ratio) mean for an ETF?", "options": ["The maximum return of the fund", "The annual total cost of the fund as a percentage", "The tax rate on fund gains", "The number of companies included"], "correct": 1, "explanation": "The TER shows what percentage of your invested amount is charged as costs each year. An ETF with 0.2% TER is far cheaper than an active fund with 1.5% — and over 30 years that difference is enormous."},
    {"question": "What should a young investor do when the market drops 30%?", "options": ["Sell everything immediately and switch to cash", "Ignore the situation, stay invested and consider buying more", "Call the broker and complain", "Switch to a different currency"], "correct": 1, "explanation": "A 30% drop is not a catastrophe for a young person with a long horizon — it is a buying opportunity. Historically the market has always recovered. Those who stay invested benefit from the recovery."},
    {"question": "What is the 'time in the market' principle?", "options": ["You should only invest during business hours", "Staying invested over long periods matters more than timing entry points", "You should track the market every hour", "The market only grows in summer months"], "correct": 1, "explanation": "Attempting to time the market perfectly almost always fails. Simply staying invested — through ups and downs — delivers better results for most investors than trying to predict market moves."},
    {"question": "How does a savings plan protect you against bad market timing?", "options": ["It guarantees a fixed return regardless of market conditions", "Regular fixed contributions automatically buy more shares when prices are low", "It locks in the lowest price of the year", "It insures you against any losses"], "correct": 1, "explanation": "By investing a fixed amount regularly, you automatically buy more units when prices are low and fewer when prices are high. This dollar-cost averaging effect smooths out the impact of market timing."},
    {"question": "What does it mean to 'stay the course' as an investor?", "options": ["Only investing in index funds", "Sticking to your strategy through market turbulence without panic-selling", "Switching to safer assets every year", "Following financial news daily and adjusting accordingly"], "correct": 1, "explanation": "Staying the course means maintaining your long-term strategy even when markets are scary. The biggest investment mistakes are made during downturns by investors who abandon their plan."},
    {"question": "Which of the following best describes a 'safe haven' asset?", "options": ["A savings account with 5% guaranteed interest", "An asset that tends to hold or increase its value during market crises", "A stock that never loses value", "A government-backed investment with zero risk"], "correct": 1, "explanation": "Safe haven assets like gold, Swiss francs or certain government bonds tend to rise or hold stable when stocks fall. They add stability to a portfolio, especially during market stress."},
    {"question": "What is the main risk of putting all your savings in one company's stock?", "options": ["You pay higher brokerage fees", "If that company fails, you lose everything", "You cannot sell the stock easily", "The government will tax your gains more heavily"], "correct": 1, "explanation": "Concentration risk means a single bad outcome — a scandal, bankruptcy or industry disruption — can wipe out your entire investment. Diversification across many companies eliminates this single-stock risk."},
    {"question": "What does 'buy and hold' mean?", "options": ["Buying stocks and immediately placing a sell order", "Purchasing investments and holding them for many years without frequent trading", "Holding cash and waiting for a market crash", "Buying bonds and holding until maturity only"], "correct": 1, "explanation": "Buy and hold is the strategy of purchasing investments and keeping them for years or decades. It minimises transaction costs, avoids emotional trading decisions and lets compound interest do the heavy lifting."},
    {"question": "Why is starting to invest at 20 better than waiting until 30?", "options": ["Markets are cheaper when you are younger", "You gain 10 extra years of compound growth that can double or triple your final wealth", "Banks offer better rates to younger customers", "You pay less tax on gains if you start younger"], "correct": 1, "explanation": "Ten additional years of compounding at 7% roughly doubles your ending wealth. Someone investing CHF 200/month from age 20 will have roughly twice as much at 65 as someone who starts at 30 investing the same amount."},
